Determine how many squarish numbers there are related to the following modified conditions:
(i) Each of its digits ranges between 1 and 8 (none of the digits are 0 or 9); 
(ii) it is a perfect square; 
(iii) the first two digits, the middle two digits, and the last two digits are all perfect squares when treated as two-digit numbers;
(iv) additionally, the middle two digits must be divisible by 2.
(A) 0
(B) 1
(C) 2
(D) 3

Abby, Bernardo, Carl, and Debra play a modified game where each starts with 5 coins. The game now has 5 rounds. In each round, five balls are placed in an urn: one green, one red, one blue, and two white. The players each draw a ball at random without replacement. The player who draws the green ball gives one coin to the player who draws the red ball, and the player who draws the blue ball gives one coin to both the green and red ball drawers. What is the probability that, at the end of the fifth round, each player has exactly 5 coins?
$\textbf{(A)}\quad \dfrac{1}{207360000} 
\qquad \textbf{(B)}\quad \dfrac{1}{300000} 
\qquad \textbf{(C)}\quad \dfrac{1}{240} 
\qquad \textbf{(D)}\quad \dfrac{1}{120000} 
\qquad \textbf{(E)}\quad \dfrac{1}{600}$
